Service accounts are bound to pods?

Yes — ServiceAccounts are associated (bound) to Pods, but not in a strict “one-to-one permanent binding” sense. It’s more accurate to say:

👉 A Pod uses a ServiceAccount as its identity.

🔹 How the association works
You assign a ServiceAccount to a Pod using:

spec:
  serviceAccountName: my-service-account
Once the Pod is created:

That ServiceAccount is attached to the Pod

A token is mounted inside the Pod

The Pod uses it to authenticate with the Kubernetes API

🔹 Important clarifications
✅ 1. Binding happens at Pod creation
You cannot change the ServiceAccount of a running Pod

If you need a different one → you must recreate the Pod

✅ 2. Multiple Pods can use the same ServiceAccount
It’s not exclusive

Example:

100 Pods → can all use my-service-account

✅ 3. Default ServiceAccount
If you don’t specify one:

serviceAccountName: default
Kubernetes automatically assigns the default ServiceAccount

✅ 4. Not “binding” like RBAC
Important distinction:

ServiceAccount ↔ Pod → assignment (identity usage)

ServiceAccount ↔ Role → binding via:

RoleBinding

ClusterRoleBinding

So:

Pods use ServiceAccounts

RBAC binds permissions to ServiceAccounts

🔹 Mental model
Think of it like this:

Pod = employee

ServiceAccount = ID badge

RoleBinding = permissions assigned to that badge

🔹 Short answer
👉 Yes, ServiceAccounts are attached to Pods, and every Pod runs under one ServiceAccount, but:

Many Pods can share one ServiceAccount

The association is defined at creation time

Actual permission binding happens via RBAC

